Week 1 Goal
By the end of this week, you should be able to:
•	start the app locally
•	recognize the main folders
•	find where text and layout live
•	make 2-3 safe UI changes by yourself
•	know which files not to touch yet
________________________________________
Day 1 — Get comfortable with the repo structure
Step 1: Open the repo and just look
In Antigravity or VS Code, open the project folder.
At the top level, you should see folders like:
•	app
•	components
•	lib
•	data
•	docs
•	scripts
•	tests
Step 2: Create your own cheat sheet
Open Notepad or Word and make a file called:
repo-notes.docx or repo-notes.txt
Write this:
•	app/ = main pages and routes
•	components/ = reusable UI pieces
•	lib/ = logic and helper code
•	data/ = generated knowledge base
•	docs/ = source documents
•	scripts/ = helper scripts like ingest
•	tests/ = automated checks
This sounds basic, but it helps a lot.
Step 3: Dont edit anything yet
Just click through folders and look.
Your mission today is:
“I know where things live.”
________________________________________
Day 2 — Run the app and understand the flow
Step 1: Start the app
Open terminal in the repo folder and run:
npm install
npm run ingest
npm run dev
Then open:
http://localhost:3000
Step 2: Use the app once
Paste a sample regulatory question into the tool.
Watch carefully:
•	where do you type?
•	what button do you press?
•	what appears after?
•	what sections show up?
Write down the app flow in simple English, like:
1.	user pastes question
2.	clicks analyze
3.	app interprets request
4.	app shows results
5.	app generates plan
Step 3: Take screenshots
Take 2-3 screenshots of the running app.
This gives you a “before” view in case you later change layout.
________________________________________
Day 3 — Understand the UI structure
Today you will learn the difference between page and component.
Step 1: Open app/page.tsx
This is usually the main page.
You are not trying to understand every line.
Just scan for:
•	big section names
•	titles
•	imports from components
•	buttons or cards
Step 2: Open components/
Look for files that sound visual, like:
•	card
•	button
•	result panel
•	form
•	input
•	output
Step 3: Learn this simple rule
If you want to change:
•	wording
•	spacing
•	order of sections
•	labels
•	page layout
You usually start in:
•	app/page.tsx
•	components/
If you want to change:
•	AI behavior
•	extraction logic
•	retrieval
•	prompts
You usually start in:
•	lib/server/...
Step 4: Write this in your notes
Frontend = what users see
Backend = how the app thinks
That distinction is one of the biggest unlocks.
________________________________________
Day 4 — Make your first safe change
Today we make a tiny UI change only.
Safe Change Option A: Change a heading
Find a visible heading in app/page.tsx or a component and change it.
Example:
•	from Analyze Request
•	to Analyze Regulatory Request
Save the file and refresh browser.
If it changes on screen, great. You just made your first edit.
Safe Change Option B: Change helper text
Example:
•	“Paste request here”
•	to
•	“Paste FDA or Health Authority request here”
Safe Change Option C: Change button label
Example:
•	“Generate”
•	to
•	“Generate Response Plan”
Important
Only do one change at a time.
After each change:
•	save
•	refresh browser
•	confirm what changed
If it breaks, undo immediately.
________________________________________
Day 5 — Make a second safe change: layout only
Today you will change something visual, not logical.
Try one of these:
•	move a section higher or lower in app/page.tsx
•	adjust spacing between cards
•	change the order of two visible panels
•	add one short info box
Example
If the “Response Plan” appears below another section, try moving its component call above the other one.
Even if it looks small, this teaches you how the page is assembled.
________________________________________
Day 6 — Learn where the knowledge comes from
Today we touch data understanding, not AI logic.
Step 1: Open docs/
Look at what source files are stored there.
These are the documents the prototype uses as its “mini library.”
Step 2: Open data/copilot/evidence-corpus.json
Dont edit it. Just inspect it.
You are trying to understand:
•	what kind of text is stored
•	how chunks are organized
•	whether source names are included
Step 3: Open scripts/build-knowledge-base.ts
Again, dont edit yet.
Just look for:
•	reading docs
•	parsing files
•	writing output JSON
Key learning for today
The AI is not magically knowing your documents.
Someone turned the docs into a searchable corpus.
That “someone” is the script.
________________________________________
Day 7 — Review and lock in understanding
Today you do not build anything new.
You review what you learned.
Write answers to these 7 questions in your notes
1.	What file most likely controls the main page?
2.	Where are reusable UI parts stored?
3.	Where does backend / AI logic live?
4.	Where do source documents live?
5.	What creates the knowledge corpus?
6.	What kind of changes are safe for me right now?
7.	Which files should I not touch yet?
If you can answer those, Week 1 is successful.
________________________________________
Safe files to touch in Week 1
You can safely explore and lightly edit:
•	app/page.tsx
•	components/...
•	globals.css or basic styling files
•	text labels
•	section order
________________________________________
Dont touch yet in Week 1
Avoid editing these until you are more comfortable:
•	lib/server/llm/...
•	lib/server/copilot/...
•	token/auth files
•	API route logic
•	retrieval ranking logic
These are not impossible, just too early.
________________________________________
Your first 3 beginner changes I recommend
Do these in this order:
Change 1
Rename one visible heading
Change 2
Rename one button or helper text
Change 3
Move one section above another in the page
If you do those 3 changes successfully, your confidence will go up a lot.
________________________________________
What to do if something breaks
Dont panic.
Use this order:
1.	undo your last change
2.	save file
3.	refresh browser
4.	if still broken, restart dev server
If needed:
npm run dev
again.

